data.content:
This code **does not use `Thread.Abort`** — so there's no `Thread.Abort` migration issue here. It uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep`, all of which work fine on .NET 8.

That said, the manual thread management pattern is outdated. The modern .NET 8 equivalent:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration guidance** (for when you do encounter it):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Use `CancellationToken` + cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.Sleep()` in cancelable work | `Task.Delay(ms, cancellationToken)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` then abort | `Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(timeout))` then cancel |

`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8. The fix is always **cooperative cancellation**:

```csharp
// Pattern: replace Thread.Abort with CancellationToken
private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
{
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
}
```

Your specific code is safe to move to .NET 8 as-is — but modernizing to `Task`/`Parallel` is recommended.
